// Java — common interview follow-up questions and answers

// Q: What is the difference between backtracking and DFS?
// A: DFS explores all paths. Backtracking prunes invalid paths early
//    by checking constraints before recursing, making it far more efficient.

// Q: How do you avoid duplicates in subsets/permutations?
// A: Sort the array. At each recursion level, skip an element if it equals
//    the previous element AND the previous element was not used
//    (for permutations) or if i > start (for subsets).

// Q: When would you use DP instead of backtracking?
// A: When you only need a count or a yes/no answer (not the actual paths),
//    and when subproblems overlap. Backtracking is preferred when you need
//    to enumerate all solutions explicitly.

public class PatternReview {
    // Master template — adapt for any backtracking problem
    void backtrack(List<Integer> path, int start, int[] nums,
                   List<List<Integer>> result) {
        // 1. Base case / goal check
        result.add(new java.util.ArrayList<>(path)); // subsets: add every state

        // 2. Explore choices
        for (int i = start; i < nums.length; i++) {
            // 3. Prune (skip duplicates, check constraints)
            if (i > start && nums[i] == nums[i - 1]) continue;

            // 4. Make choice
            path.add(nums[i]);

            // 5. Recurse
            backtrack(path, i + 1, nums, result);

            // 6. Undo choice (backtrack)
            path.remove(path.size() - 1);
        }
    }
}
```

**Key Questions to Answer Before Coding:**
1. Do I need all solutions or just one? (affects return strategy)
2. Can elements be reused? (if yes, don't increment start)
3. Are there duplicates in input? (sort + skip condition)
4. What is the base case? (length match, target == 0, row == n)
5. What constraint check prevents invalid branches? (write this first)

**Interview Tip:** Walk your interviewer through these five questions before writing a single line of code. It demonstrates structured thinking and usually earns partial credit even if your implementation has a bug. Backtracking interviews are as much about the thought process as the code — narrate your pruning decisions out loud.
